@writerLLM text
Use writerLLM for polished user-facing prose when the substance is already known and the main need is clear, fluent wording.
Prefer it for final explanations, summaries, and stitched answers that must read naturally while preserving the structure requested by the user.
It should present already computed facts faithfully, not invent missing reasoning, arithmetic, or state transitions that should have been produced upstream.
Avoid it for planning, difficult hidden reasoning, exact deterministic formatting that template-eval can handle, or code generation.
